      Peloton
   =20
 =20
It is not quite right to say that John Foley, the co-founder and still tech=
nically chief executive officer of Peloton Interactive Inc., is also Peloto=
n=E2=80=99s controlling shareholder, but it=E2=80=99s close. Peloton has du=
al-class stock in which the founders and some other insiders have stock wit=
h 20 votes per share, and Foley has a lot of it; according=C2=A0to Peloton=
=E2=80=99s proxy statement, he controls 39.6% of the voting power of Peloto=
n=E2=80=99s stock, and his co-founders Thomas Cortese=C2=A0and Hisao Kushi =
own another 18%. This is not quite right either =E2=80=94=C2=A0it counts st=
ock options in a weird way[1] =E2=80=94=C2=A0but we will just go with it. I=
n practice, Foley controls a large block of super-voting stock, and along w=
ith his co-founders and fellow senior executives he has a majority of the v=
oting stock.This makes shareholder activism somewhat challenging. If you ar=
e an activist and you do not like Peloton=E2=80=99s management, you can put=
 together a zingy deck about how bad the managers are and how much money th=
ey are costing shareholders, and you can present it to Peloton=E2=80=99s bo=
ard of directors and urge them to fire the managers, but the board=E2=80=99=
s hands are somewhat tied because, if they fire the managers, the managers =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0as controlling shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0can fire them rig=
ht back and reinstate themselves. Or you can present your zingy deck to Pel=
oton=E2=80=99s other=C2=A0shareholders, hoping to lead a proxy fight that w=
ill unseat the board, but you will lose that fight because, again, the mana=
gers control a majority of the voting stock.=C2=A0There are ways around thi=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you peel off enough of Foley=E2=80=99s co-founders and =
fellow executives and venture-capital backers maybe you can get a majority =
of the stock to vote against him =E2=80=94=C2=A0but they are narrow. If you=
 are an activist shareholder looking to convince Peloton=E2=80=99s board to=
 fire Foley, the most promising avenue is probably to=C2=A0convince Foley t=
o fire himself.Here is a fun activist deck from Blackwells Capital yesterda=
y that leans heavily on the theme of =E2=80=9Ccome on man even you don=E2=
=80=99t want to be here=E2=80=9D:It  worked!Peloton Interactive Inc. Chief =
Executive Officer John Foley will step down and become executive chairman i=
n a victory for activist investor Blackwells Capital LLC, which had campaig=
ned for his departure as the fitness company struggled with declining deman=
d for its products.Barry McCarthy, former chief financial officer at Spotif=
y Technology SA, will become CEO and president, effective Feb. 9, Peloton s=
aid in a statement Tuesday. Peloton also said about 2,800 global jobs would=
 be cut, affecting around 20% of corporate positions.=C2=A0I mean, I don=E2=
=80=99t know how well it worked; =E2=80=9Cexecutive chairman and controllin=
g shareholder=E2=80=9D is still a powerful job. But the idea, at least, is =
to put Peloton=E2=80=99s day-to-day management and strategic planning into =
different hands.In a sense, the pitch here is straightforward. Blackwells d=
oes not think that Foley is very good at running Peloton. The stock market =
does not think that Foley is very good at running Peloton, in that the stoc=
k is down 80% from its highs last year and spent last week below its 2019 i=
nitial public offering price of $29. (It=E2=80=99s up today.) And Foley doe=
s not think he=E2=80=99s particularly good at running Peloton, at least if =
you believe the quotes that Blackwells selected here. If someone else takes=
 over the day-to-day running of Peloton, or the process of=C2=A0selling it =
to a better owner (and Blackwells is also pushing for a sale), then Foley w=
ill have more money (because he owns a lot of Peloton stock) and also more =
free time (because he=E2=80=99s not running Peloton). It is no fun to do a =
job that you=E2=80=99re not good at, particularly when doing that job=C2=A0=
costs you money. If you can get in a room with Foley, or just lob a PowerPo=
int deck at him, and explain =E2=80=9Chey, everyone is mad at you, you=E2=
=80=99re=C2=A0not having fun and it=E2=80=99s making you poorer,=E2=80=9D t=
hat=E2=80=99s fairly persuasive and maybe he=E2=80=99ll listen. He did!In a=
nother sense, Foley seems to have done almost enough to insulate himself fr=
om this sort of pressure. He has super-voting shares, not quite enough to b=
e a majority but enough to swat away pesky activists in most=C2=A0situation=
s. A lot of his net worth is wrapped up in Spotify, so he has economic ince=
ntives to do the value-maximizing thing, but not=C2=A0all=C2=A0of his net w=
orth is wrapped up in Spotify, and one of Blackwells=E2=80=99 big complaint=
s is that Foley sold $96 million of Peloton stock in 2021 even while profes=
sing optimism about the business.[2] One effect of selling $96 million wort=
h of stock while the stock is high and declining is that you end up with $9=
6 million, which dulls your incentives to make the stock go back up. If the=
 stock never goes back up you still have the $96 million. Most people who h=
ave $96 million and are the CEO of a public company would prefer, all in al=
l, to make the stock go up and have more money. (His remaining stock is wor=
th something like $500 million at yesterday=E2=80=99s closing price.)=C2=A0=
But it is not an absolute necessity.So, loosely speaking, if Foley found it=
 enjoyable to run Peloton poorly for the rest of his life, he could pretty =
much afford to, and pretty much nobody could stop him. And if you tweaked t=
he situation slightly =E2=80=94=C2=A0if he had sold a bit more stock, and i=
f he had slightly more of the super-voting shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that =
would go from pretty much true to completely true.[3]A lot of public-compan=
y governance operates on the assumption that the shareholders are ultimatel=
y in charge. How this actually works is complicated and indirect, and we ha=
ve  talked about how the path from =E2=80=9Cshareholders want something=E2=
=80=9D to =E2=80=9Ccompany is forced to do it by legally binding mechanisms=
=E2=80=9D is winding and uncertain. But if you are an activist, everything =
you do takes place against a backdrop of =E2=80=9Cif you ignore the shareho=
lders we can vote you out.=E2=80=9D Usually! Traditionally!=C2=A0But modern=
 U.S. public markets increasingly have the rules of private tech startups: =
The founders control the company, they can do what they want, and=C2=A0the =
shareholders have no=C2=A0binding=C2=A0power to get rid of them. All they c=
an do is appeal to the founders themselves, telling the founders that givin=
g up power will be good for=C2=A0them, that they=E2=80=99ll have more fun a=
nd also more money if they leave. The company belongs to the founders, and =
they=E2=80=99ll only leave if they want to.
