   =20
 =20
If=C2=A0you buy a book, and you read it, and you don=E2=80=99t want to read=
 it again, you can sell it. You own the book that you bought so it=E2=80=99=
s yours to do what you want with. On the other hand, you can=E2=80=99t scan=
 the book, upload it to the internet, and sell thousands of electronic copi=
es at $1 each. You don=E2=80=99t own=C2=A0the contents of the book; you don=
=E2=80=99t own the intellectual property. You own the physical printed copy=
 of the book. In the U.S., this is called the =E2=80=9Cfirst-sale doctrine.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Similarly if you buy sneakers you can resell them. You can a=
lso wear them. They=E2=80=99ll probably have some brand on them, like a Nik=
e swoosh. If someone sees you wearing the sneakers they might say =E2=80=9C=
hey cool shoes are those Nikes=E2=80=9D and you can say =E2=80=9Cthey sure =
are, they=E2=80=99re the new Air Jordan 420s=E2=80=9D or whatever and they =
might say =E2=80=9Coh wow those are ultra rare and cool=E2=80=9D and you ca=
n be like =E2=80=9CI know.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0What if you tried to separate out =
that rare coolness from the shoes? What if you, like, advertised that you w=
ould let people take pictures with your rare Nikes to post on social media?=
 I am not an intellectual property lawyer but I feel like eventually Nike I=
nc. would get annoyed. You own the=C2=A0shoes, sure, but Nike owns the inte=
llectual property. You can resell the shoes, but the brand belongs to Nike.=
Anyway:Nike Inc. has sued StockX LLC, accusing the online marketplace of se=
lling unauthorized digital products based on its sneakers.The lawsuit, file=
d Thursday in New York federal court, is the latest dispute involving a bra=
nd over the sale of products known as nonfungible tokens, or NFTs.Nike said=
 the sale of NFTs based on recently released iterations of sneakers such as=
 Nike Dunks and Air Jordans =E2=80=9Care likely to confuse consumers, creat=
e a false association between those products and Nike=E2=80=9D and dilute i=
ts trademarks, according to the suit. NFTs act as vouchers of authenticity =
on the blockchain for goods. =E2=80=A6Customers who buy the StockX NFTs hav=
e the option of being shipped the physical sneaker, which would take that N=
FT out of circulation, or keeping the digital asset on the blockchain, whic=
h enables it to be resold on StockX=E2=80=99s platform.In recent days, NFTs=
 of the Air Jordan 4 and the Nike Dunk Low have resold for over $500 on the=
 site, according to a review by The Wall Street Journal of data on StockX, =
more than double the retail price of the physical shoes. StockX charges cus=
tomers who sell an NFT on its platform a 3% transaction fee in addition to =
a 1% payment processing fee. On its website, StockX markets the digital goo=
ds as authentic products and exclusive NFTs.Look! If you have the choice be=
tween:=09Selling a pair of rare Nike sneakers for $250, or=09Selling the sa=
me pair of sneakers for $500=C2=A0and keeping the shoes,[7]there is really =
only one logical choice. The problem is, why should Nike let you do this? W=
hy shouldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0Nike=C2=A0do this? Nike, as the issuer of Nikes, =
should be the one selling rare Nikes and not delivering them. That makes th=
em especially rare! It=E2=80=99s one thing for StockX to sell you an Air Jo=
rdan 4 and hang onto it, but Nike can sell you an Air Jordan 69,420 and not=
 even make it! It=E2=80=99s the rarest sneaker of all! Exactly zero were ev=
er made![8] It=E2=80=99s worth millions.
