<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Peloton</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not quite right to say that John=
 Foley, the co-founder and still technically chief executive officer of Pel=
oton Interactive Inc., is also Peloton=E2=80=99s controlling shareholder, b=
ut it=E2=80=99s close. Peloton has dual-class stock in which the founders a=
nd some other insiders have stock with 20 votes per share, and Foley has a =
lot of it; according=C2=A0to Peloton=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26639604.260613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9Bcm=
NoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2Mzk4MjUvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIxMzA2NjU1L2QyMTcxNjlkZGVmM=
TRhLmh0bSN0b2MyMTcxNjlfMTI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1e4881a2" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">proxy=
 statement</a>, he controls 39.6% of the voting power of Peloton=E2=80=99s =
stock, and his co-founders Thomas Cortese=C2=A0and Hisao Kushi own another =
18%. This is not quite right either =E2=80=94=C2=A0it counts stock options =
in a weird way[1] =E2=80=94=C2=A0but we will just go with it. In practice, =
Foley controls a large block of super-voting stock, and along with his co-f=
ounders and fellow senior executives he has a majority of the voting stock.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This makes shareholder activism somewhat c=
hallenging. If you are an activist and you do not like Peloton=E2=80=99s ma=
nagement, you can put together a zingy deck about how bad the managers are =
and how much money they are costing shareholders, and you can present it to=
 Peloton=E2=80=99s board of directors and urge them to fire the managers, b=
ut the board=E2=80=99s hands are somewhat tied because, if they fire the ma=
nagers, the managers =E2=80=94=C2=A0as controlling shareholders =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0can fire them right back and reinstate themselves. Or you can present=
 your zingy deck to Peloton=E2=80=99s other=C2=A0<em>shareholders</em>, hop=
ing to lead a proxy fight that will unseat the board, but you will lose tha=
t fight because, again, the managers control a majority of the voting stock=
.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are ways around this =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0if you peel off enough of Foley=E2=80=99s co-founders and fellow e=
xecutives and venture-capital backers maybe you can get a majority of the s=
tock to vote against him =E2=80=94=C2=A0but they are narrow. If you are an =
activist shareholder looking to convince Peloton=E2=80=99s board to fire Fo=
ley, the most promising avenue is probably to=C2=A0<em>convince Foley to fi=
re himself</em>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26639604.260613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xhY2t3ZWxsc2NhcC5jb20vd3AtY29udGVudC91cGxvYWRzLzIwMjIvMDIvQldfUGVsb3Rvbl9Qc=
mVzZW50YXRpb25fRmViMDcyMDIyLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbb91af88" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">fun activist deck</a> from Blackwells Capital yesterday that leans heavil=
y on the theme of =E2=80=9Ccome on man even you don=E2=80=99t want to be he=
re=E2=80=9D:</p><!--[if mso]>
<table width=3D"550"><tr><td><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/im=
ages/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/izwBVB2kFpP0/v0/-1x-1.png" width=3D"550" /></td></t=
r></table>
<div style=3D"display:none">
<![endif]--><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHB=
FdfxIU/izwBVB2kFpP0/v0/-1x-1.png" style=3D"max-width: 550px; display: block=
; width: 100%; margin-top: 20px;" /><!--[if mso]>
</div>
<![endif]--><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/26639604.260613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMDgvcGVsb3Rvbi1jZW8tZm9sZXktdG8tZGVwYXJ0LWFz=
LWJpa2VtYWtlci1wbGFucy1qb2ItY3V0cy13c2o_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIwODIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkY=
mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjA4Jn=
V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3e4b1507" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 worked</a>!</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Peloton Interactiv=
e Inc. Chief Executive Officer John Foley will step down and become executi=
ve chairman in a victory for activist investor Blackwells Capital LLC, whic=
h had campaigned for his departure as the fitness company struggled with de=
clining demand for its products.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Barry McCa=
rthy, former chief financial officer at Spotify Technology SA, will become =
CEO and president, effective Feb. 9, Peloton said in a statement Tuesday. P=
eloton also said about 2,800 global jobs would be cut, affecting around 20%=
 of corporate positions.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>I mean, I don=E2=80=99t know how well it worked; =E2=80=9Cexecutive chairm=
an and controlling shareholder=E2=80=9D is still a powerful job. But the id=
ea, at least, is to put Peloton=E2=80=99s day-to-day management and strateg=
ic planning into different hands.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a sens=
e, the pitch here is straightforward. Blackwells does not think that Foley =
is very good at running Peloton. The stock market does not think that Foley=
 is very good at running Peloton, in that the stock is down 80% from its hi=
ghs last year and spent last week below its 2019 initial public offering pr=
ice of $29. (It=E2=80=99s up today.) And Foley does not think he=E2=80=99s =
particularly good at running Peloton, at least if you believe the quotes th=
at Blackwells selected here. If someone else takes over the day-to-day runn=
ing of Peloton, or the process of=C2=A0selling it to a better owner (and Bl=
ackwells is also pushing for a sale), then Foley will have more money (beca=
use he owns a lot of Peloton stock) and also more free time (because he=E2=
=80=99s not running Peloton). It is no fun to do a job that you=E2=80=99re =
not good at, particularly when doing that job=C2=A0<em>costs you money</em>=
. If you can get in a room with Foley, or just lob a PowerPoint deck at him=
, and explain =E2=80=9Chey, everyone is mad at you, you=E2=80=99re=C2=A0not=
 having fun and it=E2=80=99s making you poorer,=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s fai=
rly persuasive and maybe he=E2=80=99ll listen. He did!</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">In another sense, Foley seems to have done almost enough to ins=
ulate himself from this sort of pressure. He has super-voting shares, not q=
uite enough to be a majority but enough to swat away pesky activists in mos=
t=C2=A0situations. A lot of his net worth is wrapped up in Spotify, so he h=
as economic incentives to do the value-maximizing thing, but not=C2=A0<em>a=
ll=C2=A0</em>of his net worth is wrapped up in Spotify, and one of Blackwel=
ls=E2=80=99 big complaints is that Foley sold $96 million of Peloton stock =
in 2021 even while professing optimism about the business.[2] One effect of=
 selling $96 million worth of stock while the stock is high and declining i=
s that you end up with $96 million, which dulls your incentives to make the=
 stock go back up. If the stock never goes back up you still have the $96 m=
illion. Most people who have $96 million and are the CEO of a public compan=
y would prefer, all in all, to make the stock go up and have more money. (H=
is remaining stock is worth something like $500 million at yesterday=E2=80=
=99s closing price.)=C2=A0But it is not an absolute necessity.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So, loosely speaking, if Foley found it enjoyable to r=
un Peloton poorly for the rest of his life, he could pretty much afford to,=
 and pretty much nobody could stop him. And if you tweaked the situation sl=
ightly =E2=80=94=C2=A0if he had sold a bit more stock, and if he had slight=
ly more of the super-voting shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that would go from p=
retty much true to completely true.[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lo=
t of public-company governance operates on the assumption that the sharehol=
ders are ultimately in charge. How this actually works is complicated and i=
ndirect, and we have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/26639604.260613/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMjEtMDUtMjcvZXh4b24tbG9zdC1hLWNsaW1hdGUtcHJveHktZmlnaHQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDI=
wODIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdX=
RtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjA4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B9b9d0987" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> talked about</a> how the path from =E2=80=9Cshareholder=
s want something=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Ccompany is forced to do it by legally=
 binding mechanisms=E2=80=9D is winding and uncertain. But if you are an ac=
tivist, everything you do takes place against a backdrop of =E2=80=9Cif you=
 ignore the shareholders we can vote you out.=E2=80=9D Usually! Traditional=
ly!=C2=A0But modern U.S. public markets increasingly have the rules of priv=
ate tech startups: The founders control the company, they can do what they =
want, and=C2=A0the shareholders have no=C2=A0<em>binding=C2=A0</em>power to=
 get rid of them. All they can do is appeal to the founders themselves, tel=
ling the founders that giving up power will be good for=C2=A0<em>them</em>,=
 that they=E2=80=99ll have more fun and also more money if they leave. The =
company belongs to the founders, and they=E2=80=99ll only leave if they wan=
t to.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" cellp=
adding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0">
