bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>Anyway</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nike Inc. has sued=
 StockX LLC, accusing the online marketplace of selling unauthorized digita=
l products based on its sneakers.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lawsu=
it, filed Thursday in New York federal court, is the latest dispute involvi=
ng a brand over the sale of products known as nonfungible tokens, or NFTs.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nike said the sale of NFTs based on recentl=
y released iterations of sneakers such as Nike Dunks and Air Jordans =E2=80=
=9Care likely to confuse consumers, create a false association between thos=
e products and Nike=E2=80=9D and dilute its trademarks, according to the su=
it. NFTs act as vouchers of authenticity on the blockchain for goods. =E2=
=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Customers who buy the StockX NFTs ha=
ve the option of being shipped the physical sneaker, which would take that =
NFT out of circulation, or keeping the digital asset on the blockchain, whi=
ch enables it to be resold on StockX=E2=80=99s platform.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">In recent days, NFTs of the Air Jordan 4 and the Nike Dunk Lo=
w have resold for over $500 on the site, according to a review by The Wall =
Street Journal of data on StockX, more than double the retail price of the =
physical shoes. StockX charges customers who sell an NFT on its platform a =
3% transaction fee in addition to a 1% payment processing fee. On its websi=
te, StockX markets the digital goods as authentic products and exclusive NF=
Ts.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look! If you have the choi=
ce between:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; m=
argin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Selling a pair of rare=
